In this article, President Joseph R. Biden Jr. proclaims June 2023 as Black Music Month in the United States. He pays homage to the legends of American music who have shaped the country's cultural landscape and influenced music worldwide. The article highlights how Black music is rooted in African rhythms and the experience of slavery and struggle in America. Enslaved people used music as a means of expressing their hopes, dreams, and hardships. Black music genres such as spirituals, gospel, blues, R&B, rock and roll, jazz, pop, rap, and hip-hop have played a significant role in shaping American culture. President Biden emphasizes his administration's support for American creators and communities, including investments in arts and humanities organizations and assistance for venues affected by the COVID-19 pandemic. He also acknowledges the contributions of legendary Black musicians and encourages the celebration of Black music and the promotion of awareness and appreciation for it.